Christmas shelf styling is some of my absolute favorite holiday decorating! Here are my tips for making your shelves come alive at Christmas 👇🏻 
💫 Start with larger pieces - usually artwork or large-scale object like urns or bigger Christmas trees
💫 Swap out your art prints for winter and Christmas themed prints 
💫 An easy Christmas accessory is a bowl or compote filled with ornaments - it works every time!
💫 Group like objects together for impact - in this case all the bottle brush trees read as one since they’re in a grouping
💫 Sprinkle in Christmas accessories with your regular objects. On our shelves the glitter Santas and gold starburst make everything feel festive.
💫 Candles of all types are perfect this time of year! I even used a textured drinking glass as a votive holder! 
💫 Let me know if this was helpful! You can shop our shelves in the @shop.ltk app or the link in bio!

I’ve been doing this easy holiday trick for as long as I can remember! In our very first, 900-square-foot apartment, I went down to the big bushes in front of our home and trimmed tons of evergreen clippings and sprinkled them everywhere. 🌲 Eleven years later and it’s still a favorite trick! Grab a $3.99 bundle at good ‘ole TJs if you don’t have access to evergreen branches (or want to avoid bugs, which is why I switched to store-bought 😆). Add them on shelves, in bowls, nestled into trays or woven through faux garland. It adds that holiday feeling but isn’t quite as much of a commitment as fresh garland. ✨ Let me know if you give this trick a try!

I share a lot of @homegoods shopping trips in stories and every time I get many messages saying that my Home Goods is so much better than yours. Let me let you in on a little secret...it’s not! 🤫 They all get the same stuff! Here are my best Home Goods shopping tips:
🛋 Go OFTEN: If you want the best finds you need to pop in 1-3 x a week. I think lots of people go once a month or less, don’t see anything they like, and then get frustrated that their store isn’t “good.” The key is to go often because the inventory is constantly changing!
🛋 Download the Home Goods app and follow your local stores. They post photos every single day of several items. That’s how I scored my arched console - saw it on the app, hopped in the car, drove straight there and made her mine! 
🛋 Look carefully. Sometimes it’s hard to see everything, so take your time and really examine each aisle, don’t just glance. Look high, bend down low, and take a second pass coming from the opposite direction. There have been plenty of things I’ve spotted my second or third time down an aisle! 
Happy hunting!

It’s time to get those zinnia seeds in the ground! I plant mine from @floretflower seeds after the last frost (mid-April) and by June I have a gorgeous harvest! Can you believe all these flowers came from about 10 seeds?! Here are my best zinnia tips
🌸 Plant seeds right in the ground or garden bed after the risk of frost has passed (I don’t bother starting these indoors - they’re hearty and quick growers)
🌸 they like full sun and lots of it ☀️
🌸 after they’ve passed the seedling stage (several inches tall with about 5 or 6 leaves) I fertilize with miracle grow
🌸 water daily, preferably at the soil and not from the top, as they’re prone to powdery mildew
🌸 when flowers appear, take them by the stem and do the wiggle test - if the flower still wiggles and flops, it’s not ready for harvest. If it’s more stationary and solid, it can be cut
🌸 cut as far down as you can, just above the next set of leaves with a bud (or at a y joint). This promotes more blooms
🌸 After enjoying your blooms, let them dry out, then rub them to remove the seeds. Save them to plant next year! 
🌸 Was this helpful? Hit SAVE to keep these tips handy for growing season!

Builder basic open concept doesn’t have to be boring! Here are my best tips for decorating an open concept space 👇🏻
🛋 1. Use rugs to define unique spaces and visually ground furniture. Size/scale is key here! If you have an open concept space, chances are you’ll need a ver large rug (usually 9x12 and up). Make sure the front feet of all furniture goes on the rug. 
🛋 2. If you don’t have built ins or architectural features, fake them! I faked the look of built ins around the fireplace with floating shelves paired with cabinets on each side. 
🛋 3. Switch out and add lighting. I switched the heavy black fan for a a sleek white one that visually disappears, and added sconces to the fireplace to create more interest. Let your lighting be the “jewelry” that dresses up a plain space. 
🛋 4. Create interest through adding layers of accessories. Hang art and mirrors, consider layering a rug, add coffee table book stacks topped with accessories, mix and match pillow patterns, and bring in greenery (real or faux) to bring the space to life.

✨ It’s peak limelight season and I couldn’t be happier! ✨ This is your sign to go ahead and plant a limelight bush or seven and enjoy these gorgeous blooms! Here’s why I love limelight hydrangeas:
✨ They’re fast-growing. We planted these as small shrubs in 2020, and look how big they’ve gotten in just three years - nearly as tall as I am!
✨ They can take full sun. Most hydrangeas need shade, but limelights (and a few other varieties) are panicle hydrangeas which can handle sun or shade.
✨ They’re low maintenance. You don’t need a green thumb! All I do is trim them down in late winter, and fertilize in April and June, though technically they would be fine without any of that. They’re pretty hardy and will grow even if you don’t do much to them!
✨ They’re gorgeous as cut flowers and dry beautifully! I have bunches of limelights from past seasons around my house, dried and still looking lovely.
✨ They go from green to white to pink and each shade is lovelier than the last! I especially love to cut them to dry them when they’re fully pink, just before the first frost.

This reorganization was all about what works best for our family and how we function. Here are a few of my best tips for organizing your pantry to not only look pretty but meet your needs:
🫙 Create zones: I moved our daily lunch box supplies from an inaccessible cabinet to a pantry shelf and I think this will work so much better for us! There is also a snack zone, paper goods zone and baking zone.
🫙 Think through functionality: I went so far as to sketch our pantry and where I thought everything should go. I also listed every food item we keep on hand and how it should be stored before starting.

🍁 AUTUMN STYLING 🍁 Styling your home for the seasons doesn’t have to be complicated. Here are my favorite tips and tricks for styling your space for each new season
🍁 Use “base decor” and keep it the same through the seasons. In this case, I generally use a tray and vase on my coffee table, a stack of books, my favorite marble bowl and candles. These are timeless pieces that can stick with every season.
🍁 Then, change the details around your base decor. Fall foliage in your vase, pumpkins filling a bowl, a new color of candle in your taper holders, books with warmer tones, a pile of velvet pumpkins adorning your tray.
🍁 I’m being a little risky here in keeping my summer blue linen pillows. A richer hue might be more “fall” but I truly love my current pillow combo so I’m making it work. I say use what you love and it will come together! 
🍁 Fall and winter can handle more “layers” in decor so they feel more cozy. I tend to pare down a bit in spring and summer and later up in the cooler months. Layered pieces like a brass leaf tray add depth and interest to your decor.

These three things are, in my opinion, the most important elements of decorating for Christmas! Ok maybe a tree too 😉 But if you’re going to invest your holiday decor money into anything, choose these three first for the biggest impact! 
🌿 Greenery, both real and faux, is the number one thing that makes a space “feel” like the holidays. Garland, wreaths and sprigs of pine are the absolute most important part of the recipe, in my opinion. In fact, after years of pouring through holiday mags and Pinterest inspo, I realized the holiday images I was most drawn to were beautiful spaces, where largely the only true Christmas decor in them was greenery of some kind. Nothing will create a holiday home faster and with more sophistication! 
🎀 Ribbon is my next choice because you can use it anywhere, it is inexpensive, and you can change your color palette just with a few strands of pretty ribbon. Try it on stockings, wreaths, packages, candlesticks, draped from sconces, vases and tree branches. Tons of bang for the buck! 
🕯And last but not least, candles of all shapes and sizes bring in cozy holiday elegance. Simple taper candles can add height to a vignette, and candles in festive shapes (like those shaped like ornaments or Santa or trees…the possibilities are endless!) bring in holiday charm while doubling as useful decor. Plus the scent of the holidays is one of the best parts! 
🌲So, if I could only use three things in my home, these are what I would choose to bring in the holiday spirit! Honorable mention to bells of all kinds, winter art prints and simple glass ornaments ☺️ What would you choose as your favorites??
